I analysed the website https://littleway.com.au to identify potential cybersecurity weaknesses.

Firstly, the website does not clearly display a privacy policy. 
This creates uncertainty about how user data (such as booking details or contact form submissions) is collected, stored, and protected.

Additionally, there is no visible indication of advanced security measures such as CAPTCHA or input validation on forms. 
This may make the website vulnerable to spam submissions or automated attacks.

Another weakness is the lack of visible user security awareness features, such as warnings about phishing or secure communication practices.
This can increase the risk of users trusting fake communications pretending to be from the business.

Furthermore, small business websites like this often rely on third-party integrations (e.g., booking systems or embedded services),
which may introduce additional security risks if not properly managed.

These observations show that even though the website functions well for business purposes, 
there are several potential security weaknesses related to data protection, user awareness, and system security practices.
